Assignment and grading practices in a university LMS

Author

Jayson Webb, PhD


jayson.m.webb@gmail.com

Published

August 23, 2023

Introduction

This brief note is an examination of a sample of data from an LMS system at a large research university. The goal was to see if there were any patterns in the timeliness of when assignments were graded relative to the due date and relative to other assignments. The data had already been anonymized and aggregated across individuals, so I only had data per assignment for selected classes in the LMS which included the latest and earliest graded dates for assignments along with the due dates. Figure 1 below is an attempt to visualize when assignments are graded.

The x-axis is the difference between the latest graded date and the due date. So, the further right we move on that axis, the later, relative to the due date, the latest graded assignment was entered into the LMS. The y-axis is the difference between the earliest and latest graded dates. So, as we move up the y-axis, the spread between the earliest and latest dates increases. The color coding represents how late in the term the due date occurs. Points that are closer to the blue/purple colors have a due date early in the semester. The more orange/yellow color indicates a due date later in the term. The points are transparent, so a more saturated color indicates that many points overlap, whereas fainter points are fewer in number. Two semesters are included here, a spring and fall semester, each of which are 115 days. Each axis is 120 days long.

There are three clear groupings in the data.

Along the left edge, going up the y-axis, we see a group of assignments where the latest graded dates are all within 1 day of the due date, but that are graded throughout the semester, as indicated by the large spread between the earliest and latest graded dates. These are assignments that had a due date set late in the semester (we can see by the orange color) but allowed assignments to be submitted throughout the semester. The left edge data makes up about 27% of the data.

Along the bottom edge, going across the x-axis, are a set of assignments that were all graded within 1 day of each other (latest - earliest graded dates), but were graded more than 1 day after the due date, so these points don’t overlap with the left edge. This accounts for about 24% of the data. Some of these were graded long after the due date. You can see points stretching all the way out past 100 days past the due date. This seems to indicate a lack of timeliness in giving feedback for these assignments.

The remainder of the data (about 49%) lies in the middle portion of the graph. Much of it lies along a 45 degree line, indicating that the time between the latest graded date and both the due date and the earliest graded date increase together.

It’s an interesting exercise to mouse over the points and look for patterns in these three different groupings. For example, many of the assignments in the left edge grouping have the words “Learning Curve” in the assignment name.

Conclusions

The goal of this analysis was to see if there were any patterns in the timeliness of when assignments were graded relative to the due date and relative to other assignments. Three clear patterns emerged, the left edge, bottom edge and middle groupings in Figure 1. About 1/4 of the data fell into each of the edge groupings with the other half falling in the middle. Next steps will be to investigate each of these groupings to reveal their characteristics and decide if any action needs to be taken for some types of assignments. For example, looking at the bottom edge groupings, there are a lot of assignments that are all graded within 1 day of each other, but they are graded 10 or more days after the due date. This seems like a problem with timely grading.
